[[Image:Tanec folk ensemble Macedonia 4.jpg|right|thumb|500px|Tanec]]<br />
'''Hasapiko''' ([[Greek language|Greek]]: <U+03C7><U+03B1><U+03C3><U+03AC><U+03C0><U+03B9><U+03BA><U+03BF>, also transliterated hassapiko, hasapika and hasapico) is a [[Greece|Greek]] traditional dance. It is also called <U+03C7><U+03B1><U+03C3><U+03AC><U+03C0><U+03B9><U+03BA><U+03BF><U+03C2> <U+03C7><U+03CC><U+03C1><U+03BF><U+03C2> or simply <U+03C7><U+03B1><U+03C3><U+03AC><U+03C0><U+03B9><U+03BA><U+03BF><U+03C2> (hasapikos horos, chas<U+00E1>pikos, khas<U+00E1>pikos, has<U+00E1>pikos). The name comes from the word "butcher" (<U+03C7><U+03B1><U+03C3><U+03AC><U+03C0><U+03B7><U+03C2>). The dance originated among members of the [[Butcher's Guild]] in [[Constantinople]] in [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] times, and was originally called <U+03BC><U+03B1><U+03BA><U+03B5><U+03BB><U+03BB><U+03AC><U+03C1><U+03B9><U+03BA><U+03BF><U+03C2> <U+03C7><U+03BF><U+03C1><U+03CC><U+03C2> (makellarikos horos), which is still the proper term in [[katharevousa]] (purist Greek). Some Greeks, however, reserve the latter term only for the fast version of the dance.

The slow version of the dance is called <U+03C7><U+03B1><U+03C3><U+03AC><U+03C0><U+03B9><U+03BA><U+03BF> <U+03B2><U+03B1><U+03C1><U+03CD> (hasapiko vary) or <U+03C7><U+03B1><U+03C3><U+03AC><U+03C0><U+03B9><U+03BA><U+03BF><U+03C2> <U+03B2><U+03B1><U+03C1><U+03CD><U+03C2> (hasapikos varys) and generally employs a 4/4 tempo.

The fast version of the dance uses a 2/4 [[rhythm]]. It is variously called <U+03B3><U+03C1><U+03AE><U+03B3><U+03BF><U+03C1><U+03BF> <U+03C7><U+03B1><U+03C3><U+03AC><U+03C0><U+03B9><U+03BA><U+03BF>, <U+03B3><U+03C1><U+03AE><U+03B3><U+03BF><U+03C1><U+03BF><U+03C2> <U+03C7><U+03B1><U+03C3><U+03AC><U+03C0><U+03B9><U+03BA><U+03BF><U+03C2>, <U+03BC><U+03B1><U+03BA><U+03B5><U+03BB><U+03BB><U+03AC><U+03C1><U+03B9><U+03BF><U+03C2> <U+03C7><U+03BF><U+03C1><U+03CC><U+03C2>; <U+03C7><U+03B1><U+03C3><U+03B1><U+03C0><U+03BF><U+03C3><U+03AD><U+03C1><U+03B2><U+03B9><U+03BA><U+03BF> (grigoro hasapiko, grigoros hasapikos, makellarios horos, sousta and hasaposerviko - the latter a reference to [[Serbia|Serbian]] and other Balkan Slavic influences on this version of the dance).

Hasapiko served as a base for the [[Sirtaki]].
Other dances that have a similar dance motif are the [[Arkan]] of the Ukraine,[[ Hora]] of Israel, the [[Debke]] of the Arab countries, the [[Kasapsko Horo]] of Bulgaria, the [[Kasapsko Kolo]] of Serbia, the [[Lesnoto]] of FYROM, the [[Soorch Bar]] of Armenia and the Kasap Havasi of Turkey.
